Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In 2 of the past 3 years, the number of reported cases of tularemia
in Germany has been higher. The 2005 'bump' was caused by a single
cluster noted below, but it is not clear that this was the case with
the 2007 'bump'.

Although classically transmitted to man via infected animals such as
rabbits or a tick vector, infection with _Francisella tularensis_ (a
Category A biowarfare disease) may be acquired from contact with soil
or water harboring the bacterium. Although tularemia pneumonia, which
did not occur in this outbreak, is the form of the disease associated
with biological terrorism, it may also occur naturally, as is
exemplified by the sporadic case described in New York City and the
outbreak among gardeners on Martha's Vineyard, both cited in past
ProMED-mail postings below.

Regarding water-related outbreaks of tularemia, outbreaks include 64
cases in Dagestan, Russia associated with a flood-plain swamp (1), 49
cases in Tuscany, Italy linked to an unchlorinated water system (2),
and an outbreak in the Smolensk province of Russia also attributed to
contamination of a water supply (3).

A previous cluster of tularemia with 10 cases including one death
occurred in Germany in 2005 in the Hesse state just north of
Baden-Wuerttemberg. Baden-Wuerttemberg is a Land (state) of the
Federal Republic of Germany in the southwestern part of the country
to the east of the Upper Rhine and can be seen on a map of the country at
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baden-W%C3%BCrttemberg>.

References
----------
1. Tikhenko NI, Efremenko VI, Omarieva E, et al: [Outbreak of
tularemia in the Republic of Dagestan] Zh Mikro Epidemiol Immunobiol
2001; 6 (Suppl): 68-72.
2. Greco D, Allegrini G, Tizzi T, et al: A waterborne tularemia
outbreak. Eur J Epidemiol 1987; 3: 35-8.
